              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3937614-terri?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3937614-terri?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3937614-terri?shelf=high-fantasy">high-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer370953021" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4041386188198828223">Daja’s book started out very interesting, with our young smith-mage finding twin girls with ambient powers. Jory (whose name is Jorality, which cracks me up because it sounds funny and I like it) is a cook mage and Nia is a wood/carpentry mage. Daja teaches them how to meditate, but Jory is hyperactive and distracts Nia, so Daja eventually has to separate them. Nia learns the more traditional quiet, breathing meditation and Jory learns a form of staff meditation wherein she repeats physical patt</span>
  <span id="freeText4041386188198828223" style="display:none">Daja’s book started out very interesting, with our young smith-mage finding twin girls with ambient powers. Jory (whose name is Jorality, which cracks me up because it sounds funny and I like it) is a cook mage and Nia is a wood/carpentry mage. Daja teaches them how to meditate, but Jory is hyperactive and distracts Nia, so Daja eventually has to separate them. Nia learns the more traditional quiet, breathing meditation and Jory learns a form of staff meditation wherein she repeats physical patterns and eventually learns to fall into her quiet place in her head. I thought that was very cool, because I’m not sure I could sit still long enough to meditate quietly. I’d much rather have a backup plan like whacking around with my staff and getting in the zone. Also, I think it’d be fun to hit things. (Yes, I’m feeling aggressive today, why do you ask?)<br /><br />Daja befriends a man named Ben, a widower who lost his family in a fire and has dedicated his life to teaching townspeople how to fight fires. Another reviewer mentioned it on GoodReads, that she gets bad touch feelings from Niko and Tris in Tris’s Book, and a I got a similar feeling in this book. Ben constantly mentions how he doesn’t see Daja as a child, and she doesn’t act like a teenager (true), and at one point mentions that he loves her. He gave me distinct “creeper alert!” feelings throughout the book. I was always very glad when Daja wasn’t alone, or when Frostpine casually hung around when she was working on the living metal gloves for Ben.<br /><br />That got me wondering: is this a theme anyone else has noticed in Pierce novels? In the Wild Magic series, Daine and Numair eventually get together, but Daine is 17 and Numair is in his thirties (I think), so it’s not so far out of the realm of possibility for the setting of the novel. It’s just that I could easily see Pierce creating this same kind of situation between a few of the Circle kids and their mentors, particularly Daja and Frostpine, and it kind of ooks me out, especially since it’s YA. While I’m not saying what YA should or shouldn’t do, I don’t think it’s good to normalize relationships where one party is so much older and mature than the other party. In the books, the adult characters aren’t shady, but in life, they might be. I still love Tamora Pierce’s novels, and even though I was a little hesistant, I loved the Wild Magic series. I just see a pattern and I’m not sure if I’m over-analyzing or what. Is this an author creating a mentorship/parent/close friend relationship between an adult and a kid who has been isolated/mistreated/orphaned/whatever, or is there something else at work?</span>
  <a data-text-id="4041386188198828223" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

