    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1166303634" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1166303634" />
    <a title="cookiemonger" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19393388-cookiemonger"><img alt="cookiemonger" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1557981054p2/19393388.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1166303634?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="cookiemonger" class="user" itemprop="url" name="cookiemonger" href="/user/show/19393388-cookiemonger">cookiemonger</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780590396554" href="/book/show/4008201-cold-fire">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1166303634" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4407229606859913939">I almost typed Fireburg, and that would have been a good title. There are so many housefires in this book, it would have been deeply offensive for anyone to ever use the phrase, &quot;get on like a house afire.&quot; Although I probably would have laughed, because I can be a jerk like that.<br/><br/>The series seems to be incredibly aware of the formulaic nature of this quartet. In a good way, but not a great way. There are some things that get changed up, that are very good indeed. Daja finds two students--twins, </span>
  <span id="freeText4407229606859913939" style="display:none">I almost typed Fireburg, and that would have been a good title. There are so many housefires in this book, it would have been deeply offensive for anyone to ever use the phrase, "get on like a house afire." Although I probably would have laughed, because I can be a jerk like that.<br /><br />The series seems to be incredibly aware of the formulaic nature of this quartet. In a good way, but not a great way. There are some things that get changed up, that are very good indeed. Daja finds two students--twins, which are something not unfamiliar to Pierce--and I only despised one of them. She was exactly the same as the other two obnoxious brats, yet less present. The other twin, I loved. She was quiet and polite and why don't I see more of those in fiction?<br /><br />Seriously, annoying and bratty are not compelling traits. Also, amiable and polite are not boring. They're just less annoying.<br /><br />The most obvious change is that almost all of the story revolves around Daja and what is going on with her. The teaching is an inconvenience that she has to keep telling herself not to shirk, and she is decent at it. She also only has to teach the twins meditation, so she's far better off than Sandry or Briar.<br /><br />What is going on with her is that she alternately hates the snowy winter and thinks snow is so great (no really, she makes a rather nasty remark about this type of winter being uncivilised and then literally the next chapter has her saying how great snow is) and she meets this guy who is a firefighter. Which is awesome.<br /><br />Except of course it isn't. I had this guy pegged as Bad almost immediately, but then I realised that this may have been because a friend made me read the reveal years ago. Fair enough.<br /><br />Again, not a spoiler because it happens very early on and knowing what this guy is doing makes up a lot of the book's story and impact. And boy does it ever impact. After Sandry's book, I was almost prepared for more dead babies, but it's still a little too much for YA, in my opinion. I'll admit I'm sensitive when it comes to this stuff.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[It looks a bit worse when you think about the fact that the murder of the guy's mother is unexpectedly vague. Maybe I'm an awful person, but I wanted to know how she was killed. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Even though the reader gets to know what's going on the whole time, Daja never really looks stupid or blind. A few times, she starts to piece things together, only to interrupted or to tell herself not to be dumb/suspicious/whatever. I felt sorry for her at the end.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4407229606859913939" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

