  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_32235973" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/32235973" />
    <a title="Somesuchlike" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1478257-somesuchlike"><img alt="Somesuchlike" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1317688247p2/1478257.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/32235973?book_show_action=true">May 09, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Somesuchlike" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Somesuchlike" href="/user/show/1478257-somesuchlike">Somesuchlike</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780439981637" href="/book/show/1124996.Cold_Fire">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1478257-somesuchlike?shelf=genre-speculative-fiction">genre-speculative-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1478257-somesuchlike?shelf=author-tamora-pierce">author-tamora-pierce</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1478257-somesuchlike?shelf=series-circle-opens">series-circle-opens</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1478257-somesuchlike?shelf=type-childrens-fiction">type-childrens-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1478257-somesuchlike?shelf=genre-fantasy">genre-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer32235973" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10996935559439022489">For the first (and only) time reading this series, I moved unto unknown territory with Cold Fire. I&apos;d read at least some of the other volumes, but I knew nothing about Cold Fire other than that it featured Daja, a set of magical twins, and that it&apos;s a bit longer than the rest of the series.<br/><br/>Turns out, it is twisted. This would be a disturbing plot for a grown-up book, and Cold Fire is aimed at twelve-year-olds. It&apos;s a kind of psychological police thriller, with magic. Pitting Daja against a seria</span>
  <span id="freeText10996935559439022489" style="display:none">For the first (and only) time reading this series, I moved unto unknown territory with Cold Fire. I'd read at least some of the other volumes, but I knew nothing about Cold Fire other than that it featured Daja, a set of magical twins, and that it's a bit longer than the rest of the series.<br /><br />Turns out, it is twisted. This would be a disturbing plot for a grown-up book, and Cold Fire is aimed at twelve-year-olds. It's a kind of psychological police thriller, with magic. Pitting Daja against a serial arsonist is a master-stroke; she's simultaneously in her element and pushed to her limits. Daja's always been depicted as strong, both physically and emotionally, but also with a certain vulnerability that really comes across here.<br /><br />And the plot, again: one of the most disturbing twists I've come across in a children's book, though I do wonder if the identity of the arsonist should have been revealed to the audience a little later.<br /><br />The other part of the narrative, Daja's discovery of two new mages, I found a little lacking. For one thing, Cold Fire is alone in the quartet in that there's no sections from the point of view of Jory or Nia. We also don't see Nia's power in action early on – when it's determined she has woodworking magic, Daja comments that she's always loved whittling, but I don't remember that being mentioned.<br /><br />I'd also have liked to have seen Nia and Jory more involved in the main plot, seeing as they're supposed to be main characters. But I am pleased that the standard 'magical twins' trope has been avoided – they have totally different kinds of magic.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10996935559439022489" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

